snippet.textDisplay:
Djokovic has well and truly solved the Nadal-riddle on every surface but clay. The only — and I mean only — player who's capable of outplaying the Djoker in this form is the Fed. Mostly in a best-of-three sets match...but, as Wimbledon showed, possibly in a best-of-five. And there's a reason for this – the Fed's unparalled variety . (Rafa is extremely skilled but he doesn't play with variety unless he simply has too.)

For those of you interested in statistics, notice how the Fed has a DR (dominance ratio --> % of return points won divided by % of serve points lost) greater than 1 (!) against the Djoker despite trailing in their H2H. That this is a calculation across 49 matches is what makes it even more astonishing.

http://www.tennisabstract.com/cgi-bin/player.cgi?p=NovakDjokovic#head-to-heads-h

Equally piquant, given their rather lopsided H2H, is the (very respectable) 0.97 DR that the Fed has against Rafa.

Coming back to the Djoker: he'll never have Fed's "style" and his overhead will always remain comical but he may end up being the greatest of the 'Big 3'. And, my goodness, that backhand down-the-line! One of modern tennis's very greatest shots.

snippet.textDisplay: There are several players who I really like but Djokovic is at the top of the list.  I will root for him against anyone he plays.   I definitely want him to win a few more grand slams so he can be right up there with Nadal and Federer in title count.  When the big 3 wrap up their careers, I want Djokovic to have at least one more than either of the other two.  I like all of them and am grateful that I have been able to watch their stunning dominance over the better part of the last 20 years but my heart gravitates towards Novak as my ultimate favorite.
